title.narrative: SECOND RURAL AND MAIN ROADS PROJECT

description.narrative: The overarching goal of the project is to contribute reducing rural poverty and build social cohesion by improving and maintaining access in rural areas to markets, schools, health centers and other social and economic infrastructure through broadened community participation. By emphasizing beneficiary involvement, the project will assure that local development decisions reflect the needs and priorities of rural communities.

title.narrative: Strengthening local capacity (Creation of UTAVs and FVRs)

comment.narrative: UTAVs-refers to the technical administration units in the mancomunidades while the FVRs refers to the regional road funds.

target.value: UTAV and FVR fully operational in each Mancomunidad

actual.value: UTAVs fully operational in both mancomunidades

comment.narrative: THe FVRs were redesigned to include a Head and a Treasurer in each mancomunidad

title.narrative: Maintenance through ME on a pilot basis - ADIMAM (number of ME in operation)

comment.narrative: ADIMAM officials requested to stay with model of maintenance committees (COMAVIs) where work is voluntary and not paid. 61 COMAVIsset up in San Marcos, and an additional 119 were set up in Huehuetenango for a total of 180 COMAVIs. Project has provided tools andequipment. COMAVIs have also been trained

actual.value: 749km completed including 674km of tertiary roads under INFOM and 75km of secondary roads under DGC

comment.narrative: One core indicator for both secondary and tertiary roads (INFOM 674km, DGC 145km). Of the target 145km of secondary roads, 75 kmofsecondary roads actually completed. The rest will be completed with Government financing.

Local communities asked to replace the pathways with the periodic maintenance works. For the bridges, 21 no. could not becontracted due to contractor non-fulflllment of the bid criteria. And costs also increased from original 2003 estimates.

actual.value: 30 km of peeriodic maintenance (gravel, stone, etc) and 37 pedestrian bridges.

title.narrative: Number of kilometers of rural roads maintained

comment.narrative: Project Target for San Marcos only.
380km maintained by 61 COMAVIS in San Marcos. An extra 325km maintained by 119 COMAVIs in Huehuetenango

title.narrative: Approximately 2000m of spot improvements on municipal roads

comment.narrative: Target met under intervened roads which lead to municipal headquarters, and connect communities in the municipalities.

title.narrative: Implementation of the Social Management Plan

comment.narrative: INFOM has delivered workshops on social awareness and citizen responsibility for community road infrastructure, capacity buildingin social, technical and financial matters, accompaniment in solving arising problems e.g. resettlement, and promotion of roadmaintenance, and safety.

title.narrative: Incorporation of coordination unit in the structure of INFOM

comment.narrative: Coordination unit incorporated into INFOM structure, and in addition to project is also managing a loan with the Japanesefinancing. INFOM now has strong capacity to implement other projects.

title.narrative: Improved rural road network in MAMSOHUE and HUISTA

baseline.value: 1. 400,000 people in ADIMAM benefit from improved access (4260-GU) 2. 500,000 people do not benefit from improved access.

target.value: 1. 400,000 people from ADIMAM will continue to benefit from improved access 2. 500,000 people in Huehuetenango will be providedwith reliable access 3. Travel time reduced up to 40%

actual.value: 1. 355,000 people benefited in both San Marcos and Huehuetenango from INFOM component; and 408,820 people benefited from DGCinvestments in both departments 3. Travel time reduced up to 42%

comment.narrative: Beneficiaries separated by implementing agency (INFOM and DGC) due to restructuring during implementation

title.narrative: Strengthened institutional capacity to manage rural transport infrastructure on sustainable basis

baseline.value: 1. UTAVs and FVR non existent 2. Municipalities do not cofinance works 3. Poor road maintenance 4. No municipal contribution tooperations5. No national transport and rural roads participatory strategy 6. No strengthening of involved institutions7. Nomedium term impact evaluation done

target.value: 1. UTAVs and FVR operational 2. Municipalities cofinancing works 3. Municipalities maintaining rural network rehabilitated4.Municipal contributions to operations of at least Q75,000 per year5. National transport and rural roads participatory strategydone 6. Strengthening of involved institutions7. Medium term impact evaluation done

actual.value: 1. UTAVs and FVR operational 2. Municipalities cofinancing works 3. Municipalities maintaining rural network rehabilitated4.Municipal contributions to operations of at least Q80,000 per year5. National transport and rural roads participatory strategydone but not implemented 6. Strengthening of involved institutions7. Medium term impact evaluation done in May 2008

comment.narrative: Cofinancing percentage dropped to 15% from 25%. The mucipalities of Huista and Mamsohue were created under the project. Trainingand capacity building delivered.

target.value: 1. 20 micro-enterprises for routine road maintenance pilot. 2. 20 communities involved with about 150 worker posts. 3.Enterpreneural culture for road maintenance activities.

actual.value: 1. 180 maintenance committees created; 2. & 3. Micro-enterprises were not created but the maintenance committes have been trainedand carrying out maintenance funtions.

comment.narrative: COMAVIs in San Marcos received routine maintenance equipment and road safety gear.
